# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hashicorp-vault
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] HashiCorp is headquartered in San Francisco, but its employees are distributed across the United States, Canada, Australia, India, and Europe.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] HashiCorp offers source-available libraries and other proprietary products.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] HashiCorp was founded in 2012 by Mitchell Hashimoto and Armon Dadgar, two classmates from the University of Washington's Paul G.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] Allen School of Computer Science and Engineering .
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] Co-founder Hashimoto was previously working on open-source software called Vagrant, which became incorporated into HashiCorp.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] On 29 November 2021, HashiCorp set terms for its IPO at $68-$72 at a valuation of $13 billion.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] HashiCorp considers its workers to be remote workers first rather than coming into an office on a full-time basis.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] Around April 2021, a supply chain attack using code auditing tool codecov allowed hackers limited access to HashiCorp's customers networks.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] As a result, private credentials were leaked.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] HashiCorp revoked a private signing key and asked its customers to use a new rotated key.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] Mitchell Hashimoto resigned from the company in December 2023.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] On April 24, 2024, the company announced it had entered into an agreement to be acquired by IBM for $6.4 billion, with the transaction expected to close by the end of the same year.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] This led to the Competition and Markets Authority of the United Kingdom launching an investigation into the acquisition in late 2024.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] The deal closed on February 27, 2025 for $6.4 billion after receiving the necessary regulatory approvals.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] HashiCorp provides a suite of tools intended to support the development and deployment of large-scale service-oriented software installations.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] Each tool is aimed at specific stages in the life cycle of a software application, with a focus on automation.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] Many have a plugin-oriented architecture in order to provide integration with third-party technologies and services.
[src:hashicorp-vault/hashicorp] Additional proprietary features for some of these tools are offered commercially and are aimed at enterprise customers.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:hashicorp-vault/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] In one type of secret sharing scheme there is one *dealer* and *n* *players*.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The dealer gives a share of the secret to the players, but only when specific conditions are fulfilled will the players be able to reconstruct the secret from their shares.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The dealer accomplishes this by giving each player a share in such a way that any group of *t* (for *threshold*) or more players can together reconstruct the secret but no group of fewer than *t* players can.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Such a system is called a (*t*, *n*)-threshold scheme (sometimes it is written as an (*n*, *t*)-threshold scheme).
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing was invented independently by Adi Shamir and George Blakley in 1979.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes are ideal for storing information that is highly sensitive and highly important.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Examples include: encryption keys, missile launch codes, and numbered bank accounts.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Each of these pieces of information must be kept highly confidential, as their exposure could be disastrous; however, it is also critical that they should not be lost.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Traditional methods for encryption are ill-suited for simultaneously achieving high levels of confidentiality and reliability.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] This is because when storing the encryption key, one must choose between keeping a single copy of the key in one location for maximum secrecy, or keeping multiple copies of the key in different locations for greater reliability.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Increasing reliability of the key by storing multiple copies lowers confidentiality by creating additional attack vectors; there are more opportunities for a copy to fall into the wrong hands.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes address this problem, and allow arbitrarily high levels of confidentiality and reliability to be achieved.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing also allows the distributor of the secret to trust a group 'in aggregate'.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Traditionally, giving a secret to a group for safekeeping would require that the distributor completely trust all members of the group.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes allow the distributor to securely store the secret with the group even if not all members can be trusted all the time.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] So long as the number of traitors is never more than the critical number needed to reconstruct the secret, the secret is safe.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing schemes are important in cloud computing environments.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Thus a key can be distributed over many servers by a threshold secret sharing mechanism.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The key is then reconstructed when needed.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing has also been suggested for sensor networks where the links are liable to be tapped, by sending the data in shares which makes the task of the eavesdropper harder.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The security in such environments can be made greater by continuous changing of the way the shares are constructed.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] A secure secret sharing scheme distributes shares so that anyone with fewer than *t* shares has no more information about the secret than someone with 0 shares.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Consider for example the secret sharing scheme in which the secret phrase "password" is divided into the shares "pa––––––", "––ss––––", "––––wo––", and "––––––rd".
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] A person with 0 shares knows only that the password consists of eight letters, and thus would have to guess the password from 268 = 208 billion possible combinations.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] A person with one share, however, would have to guess only the six letters, from 266 = 308 million combinations, and so on as more persons collude.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Consequently, this system is not a "secure" secret sharing scheme, because a player with fewer than *t* secret shares is able to reduce the problem of obtaining the inner secret without first needing to obtain all of the necessary shares.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] In contrast, consider the secret sharing scheme where *X* is the secret to be shared, *Pi* are public asymmetric encryption keys and *Qi* their corresponding private keys.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] In this scheme, any player with private key 1 can remove the outer layer of encryption, a player with keys 1 and 2 can remove the first and second layer, and so on.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] A player with fewer than *N* keys can never fully reach the secret *X* without first needing to decrypt a public-key-encrypted blob for which he does not have the corresponding private key – a problem that is currently believed to be computationally infeasible.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Additionally we can see that any user with all *N* private keys is able to decrypt all of the outer layers to obtain *X*, the secret, and consequently this system is a secure secret distribution system.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Several secret-sharing schemes are said to be information-theoretically secure and can be proven to be so, while others give up this *unconditional security* for improved efficiency while maintaining enough security to be considered as secure as other common cryptographic primitives.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] For example, they might allow secrets to be protected by shares with entropy of 128 bits each, since each share would be considered enough to stymie any conceivable present-day adversary, requiring a brute force attack of average size 2127.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Note: *n* is the total number of 'players', among whom the shares are distributed, and *t* is the minimum number of players required to reveal the secret.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Instead, (1) can be performed using the binary operation in any group.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] For example, take the cyclic group of integers with addition modulo 232, which corresponds to 32-bit integers with addition defined with the binary overflow being discarded.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The secret *s* can be partitioned into a vector of *M* 32-bit integers, which we call *v*secret.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Then (*n* − 1) of the players are each given a vector of *M* 32-bit integers that is drawn independently from a uniform probability distribution, with player *i* receiving *vi*.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The secret vector can then be recovered by summing across all the players' vectors.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The difficulty lies in creating schemes that are still secure, but do not require all *n* shares.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] When space efficiency is not a concern, trivial *t* = *n* schemes can be used to reveal a secret to any desired subsets of the players simply by applying the scheme for each subset.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] For example, to reveal a secret *s* to any two of the three players Alice, Bob and Carol, create three ( ${\binom {3}{2}}$ ) different *t* = *n* = 2 secret shares for *s*, giving the three sets of two shares to Alice and Bob, Alice and Carol, and Bob and Carol.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] For example, imagine that the board of directors of a company would like to protect their secret formula.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The president of the company should be able to access the formula when needed, but in an emergency any 3 of the 12 board members would be able to unlock the secret formula together.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] One of the ways this can be accomplished is by a secret-sharing scheme with *t* = 3 and *n* = 15, where 3 shares are given to the president, and one share is given to each board member.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] In the worst case, the increase is exponential.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] This has led to the search for schemes that allow secrets to be shared efficiently with a threshold of players.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] A ramp secret sharing scheme is a secret-sharing scheme with two thresholds: groups below the lower threshold learn no information about the secret, groups at or above the upper threshold can reconstruct it, and intermediate-size groups may obtain partial information.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] This relaxation can reduce the size of shares.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Hirosuke Yamamoto's (*k*, *L*, *n*) threshold scheme is an early information-theoretic formulation of this trade-off.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] In this scheme, any *t* out of *n* shares may be used to recover the secret.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The system relies on the idea that one can construct a unique polynomial of degree *t* − 1, such that each of the *t* points lies on the polynomial.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] It takes two points to define a straight line, three points to fully define a quadratic, four points to define a cubic curve, and so on.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] That is, it takes *t* points to define a polynomial of degree *t* − 1.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The method is to create a polynomial of degree *t* − 1 with the secret as the first coefficient and the remaining coefficients picked at random.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Next find *n* points on the curve and give one to each of the players.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] When at least *t* out of the *n* players reveal their points, there is sufficient information to fit a (*t* − 1)th degree polynomial to them, the first coefficient being the secret.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] , and the secret is the point at which three shares intersect.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Two nonparallel lines in the same plane intersect at exactly one point.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Three nonparallel planes in space intersect at exactly one point.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] More generally, any *n* nonparallel (*n* − 1)-dimensional hyperplanes intersect at a specific point.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The secret may be encoded as any single coordinate of the point of intersection.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] If the secret is encoded using all the coordinates, even if they are random, then an insider (someone in possession of one or more of the (*n* − 1)-dimensional hyperplanes) gains information about the secret since he knows it must lie on his plane.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] If an insider can gain any more knowledge about the secret than an outsider can, then the system no longer has information theoretic security.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] If only one of the *n* coordinates is used, then the insider knows no more than an outsider (i.e., that the secret must lie on the *x*-axis for a 2-dimensional system).
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Each player is given enough information to define a hyperplane; the secret is recovered by calculating the planes' point of intersection and then taking a specified coordinate of that intersection.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Blakley's scheme is less space-efficient than Shamir's; while Shamir's shares are each only as large as the original secret, Blakley's shares are *t* times larger, where *t* is the threshold number of players.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Blakley's scheme can be tightened by adding restrictions on which planes are usable as shares.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The resulting scheme is equivalent to Shamir's polynomial system.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The Chinese remainder theorem can also be used in secret sharing, for it provides us with a method to uniquely determine a number *S* modulo *k* many pairwise coprime integers $m_{1},m_{2},...,m_{k}$ , given that $S<\prod _{i=1}^{k}m_{i}$ .
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] There are two secret sharing schemes that make use of the Chinese remainder theorem, Mignotte's and Asmuth-Bloom's Schemes.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] They are threshold secret sharing schemes, in which the shares are generated by reduction modulo the integers $m_{i}$ , and the secret is recovered by essentially solving the system of congruences using the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] If the players store their shares on insecure computer servers, an attacker could crack in and steal the shares.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] If it is not practical to change the secret, the uncompromised (Shamir-style) shares can be renewed.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The dealer generates a new random polynomial with constant term zero and calculates for each remaining player a new ordered pair, where the x-coordinates of the old and new pairs are the same.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Each player then adds the old and new y-coordinates to each other and keeps the result as the new y-coordinate of the secret.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] All of the non-updated shares the attacker accumulated become useless.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] An attacker can only recover the secret if he can find enough other non-updated shares to reach the threshold.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] This situation should not happen because the players deleted their old shares.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Additionally, an attacker cannot recover any information about the original secret from the update files because they contain only random information.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The dealer can change the threshold number while distributing updates, but must always remain vigilant of players keeping expired shares.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] A player might lie about his own share to gain access to other shares.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] A *verifiable secret sharing* (VSS) scheme allows players to be certain that no other players are lying about the contents of their shares, up to a reasonable probability of error.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Such schemes cannot be computed conventionally; the players must collectively add and multiply numbers without any individual's knowing what exactly is being added and multiplied.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The disadvantage of unconditionally secure secret sharing schemes is that the storage and transmission of the shares requires an amount of storage and bandwidth resources equivalent to the size of the secret times the number of shares.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] If the size of the secret were significant, say 1 GB, and the number of shares were 10, then 10 GB of data must be stored by the shareholders.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Alternate techniques have been proposed for greatly increasing the efficiency of secret sharing schemes, by giving up the requirement of unconditional security.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] One of these techniques, known as *secret sharing made short*, combines Rabin's information dispersal algorithm (IDA) with Shamir's secret sharing.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Data is first encrypted with a randomly generated key, using a symmetric encryption algorithm.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Next this data is split into N pieces using Rabin's IDA.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] This IDA is configured with a threshold, in a manner similar to secret sharing schemes, but unlike secret sharing schemes the size of the resulting data grows by a factor of (number of fragments / threshold).
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] For example, if the threshold were 10, and the number of IDA-produced fragments were 15, the total size of all the fragments would be (15/10) or 1.5 times the size of the original input.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] In this case, this scheme is 10 times more efficient than if Shamir's scheme had been applied directly on the data.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The final step in secret sharing made short is to use Shamir secret sharing to produce shares of the randomly generated symmetric key (which is typically on the order of 16–32 bytes) and then give one share and one fragment to each shareholder.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] A related approach, known as AONT-RS, applies an All-or-nothing transform to the data as a pre-processing step to an IDA.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The All-or-nothing transform guarantees that any number of shares less than the threshold is insufficient to decrypt the data.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] An information-theoretically secure *k*-of-*n* secret-sharing scheme generates *n* shares, each of size at least that of the secret itself, leading to the total required storage being at least *n*-fold larger than the secret.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] In multi-secret sharing designed by Matthew K.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Franklin and Moti Yung, multiple points of the polynomial host secrets; the method was found useful in numerous applications from coding to multi-party computations.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] In space efficient secret sharing, devised by Abhishek Parakh and Subhash Kak, each share is roughly the size of the secret divided by *k* − 1.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] This scheme makes use of repeated polynomial interpolation and has potential applications in secure information dispersal on the Web and in sensor networks.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] This method is based on data partitioning involving the roots of a polynomial in finite field.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Some vulnerabilities of related *space efficient* secret sharing schemes were pointed out later.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] They show that a scheme based on interpolation method cannot be used to implement a (*k*, *n*) scheme when the *k* secrets to be distributed are inherently generated from a polynomial of degree less than *k* − 1, and the scheme does not work if all of the secrets to be shared are the same, etc.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] A secret-sharing scheme can secure a secret over multiple servers and remain recoverable despite multiple server failures.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] The dealer may act as several distinct participants, distributing the shares among the participants.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] This is one of the major concepts behind the Vanish computer project at the University of Washington, where a random key is used to encrypt data, and the key is distributed as a secret across several nodes in a P2P network.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] In order to decrypt the message, at least *t* nodes on the network must be accessible; the principle for this particular project being that the number of secret-sharing nodes on the network will decrease naturally over time, therefore causing the secret to eventually *vanish*.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] However, the network is vulnerable to a Sybil attack, thus making Vanish insecure.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Any shareholder who ever has enough information to decrypt the content at any point is able to take and store a copy of X.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Consequently, although tools and techniques such as Vanish can make data irrecoverable within their own system after a time, it is not possible to force the deletion of data once a malicious user has seen it.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] This is one of the leading conundrums of digital rights management.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] A dealer could send *t* shares, all of which are necessary to recover the original secret, to a single recipient.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] An attacker would have to intercept all *t* shares to recover the secret, a task which is more difficult than intercepting a single file, especially if the shares are sent using different media (e.g. some over the Internet, some mailed on CDs).
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] For large secrets, it may be more efficient to encrypt the secret and then distribute the key using secret sharing.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing is an important primitive in several protocols for secure multiparty computation.
[src:hashicorp-vault/secret-sharing] Secret sharing can also be used for user authentication in a system.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Secrets engines are components which store, generate, or encrypt data.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Secrets engines are incredibly flexible, so it is easiest to think about them in terms of their function.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Secrets engines are provided some set of data, they take some action on that data, and they return a result.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Some secrets engines simply store and read data - like encrypted Redis/Memcached.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Other secrets engines connect to other services and generate dynamic credentials on demand.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Other secrets engines provide encryption as a service, totp generation, certificates, and much more.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Secrets engines are enabled at a **path** in Vault.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] When a request comes to Vault, the router automatically routes anything with the route prefix to the secrets engine.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] In this way, each secrets engine defines its own paths and properties.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] To the user, secrets engines behave similar to a virtual filesystem, supporting operations like read, write, and delete.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Most secrets engines can be enabled, disabled, tuned, and moved via the CLI or API.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Once a secrets engine is enabled, you can interact with it directly at its path according to its own API.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Use `vault path-help` to determine the paths it responds to.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Note that mount points cannot conflict with each other in Vault.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] There are two broad implications of this fact.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] The first is that you cannot have a mount which is prefixed with an existing mount.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] The second is that you cannot create a mount point that is named as a prefix of an existing mount.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Secrets engines receive a *barrier view* to the configured Vault physical storage.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] When a secrets engine is enabled, a random UUID is generated.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] This becomes the data root for that engine.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Whenever that engine writes to the physical storage layer, it is prefixed with that UUID folder.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] Since the Vault storage layer doesn't support relative access (such as `../`), this makes it impossible for an enabled secrets engine to access other data.
[src:hashicorp-vault/vault-secrets] This is an important security feature in Vault - even a malicious engine cannot access the data from any other engine.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Vault provides centralized, well-audited privileged access and secret management for mission-critical data whether you deploy systems on-premises, in the cloud, or in a hybrid environment.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] With a modular design based around a growing plugin ecosystem, Vault lets you integrate with your existing systems and customize your application workflow.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Modern software works because of **secrets**.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Secrets are sensitive, discrete pieces of information like credentials, encryption keys, authentication certificates, and other critical pieces of information your applications need to run consistently and securely.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Vault helps harden applications by centralizing secret management.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] HCP Vault Dedicated runs Vault in the cloud using the same binary as self-managed Vault Enterprise.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] It offers a consistent user experience without the hassle of managing deployment clusters or servers.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Sign up for HCP Vault Dedicated or review the HCP Vault Dedicated tutorials to learn more.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Plugins act as building blocks in Vault that let you control how data moves through your environment and how clients access that data.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Use plugins from the curated plugin registry or build custom plugins to integrate Vault in the way that makes the most sense for you workflows.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Vault encrypts data at rest and gates access to that data with configurable, robust authentication and authorization methods.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Vault generates an access token that links the client request to an internal entity and applicable security policies.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Clients interact with secrets and encryption operations based on resource paths mounted in Vault.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Vault authorizes the client request against policies set on the resource path and grants or denies access accordingly.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Throughout the process, Vault audits all activity, regardless of whether authentication or authorization succeeds so you can track interactions with mission critical systems.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Vault supports a variety of options for durable information storage.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] We recommend integrated storage for most deployments.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Integrated storage supports backup/restore workflows, high availability, and Enterprise replication features without relying on third-party systems where Vault cannot verify the security and traceability of data access.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] Vault is robust, powerful, and flexible.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] But it can also be overwhelming if you have limited or simple secret management needs.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] If your organization is just getting started with secrets management or looking to simplify an existing secrets management processes, consider starting with HCP Vault Dedicated instead of Vault.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] HCP Vault Dedicated is a managed offering of Vault that runs on the HashiCorp cloud platform.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] HCP Vault Dedicated provides a Vault Enterprise cluster without the operational overhead of planning, deploying, and managing a self-hosted Vault cluster.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] You can download Vault as a precompiled binary, install an official Community or Enterprise package with supported package managers, or clone the Vault Community repo in GitHub and build Vault from source code.
[src:hashicorp-vault/what-is-vault] To use Vault Enterprise features, you must have a valid license configured.
